The party is so numerous that it will be obliged to see Mr. Robson in "The Henrietta" in two sections.

abstract: ALBANY, May 7. -- There are a great many Democrats who are interested in the subject of the Gubernatorial nomination. Some of them have adopted the plan of sounding the Governor on it. abstract: BOSTON, May 8. -- In the cleanest possible manner the New-Yorks won from Boston to-day. They did not allow the local players to score a solitary run, and in the field played without an error of any description. abstract: BUFFALO, May 8. -- A great deal of interest is manifested in the proposed visit next week to this city, his old home, of ex-President Cleveland. He has not been here since November, 1885, when, during the first year of his Administration, he came home to vote. He then felt a great deal of interest in the result of the State election, and made a flying trip for the purpose of manifesting it.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, May 9. -- The university Trustees have decided to establish a memorial fund in memory of the late Dr. Joseph Leidy. It is hoped that at least $100,000 will be secured for the purpose. The character which the memorial will assume has not yet been definitely settled. It has been suggested that a fine structure shall be erected for the rapidly-growing archaeological collection, and that it shall be named the Leidy Museum.

abstract: TALLAHASSEE, Fla., May 11. -- The joint Democratic caucus was called to order at 8:30 tonight, and the sixty-ninth ballot for Senator was taken promptly. It resulted as follows: Call, 51; Mays, 44; Bloxham, 2; Long, 1. Call had gained two votes since the last ballot taken last Friday night. This was due to the action of Messrs. Peacock and Overstreet of the House -- the former from Lafayette, the latter from Osceola County.

abstract: CORNWALL, N.Y., May 25. -- Yesterday morning Mrs. Divine, a widow, went to church, leaving her two little girls, Nora and Janny, aged, respectively, six and four years, alone in the house. abstract: CHICAGO, May 26. -- Capt. Adrian Constantine Anson is as mad as a March hare to-night. In to-day's game he held the lead over the New-Yorks for seven innings, and just when it seemed positive that victory was going to crown his efforts the Giants made one of their characteristic spurts, and that is the cause of the big Captain's discomfiture. They scored five times, just enough to win.

abstract: NEW-ORLEANS, May 29. -- A month of legal efforts has passed and the alleged jury bribers in the Hennessy case are as far from the penitentiary as ever. The petit jury in both sections of the Criminal District Court was discharged to-day, and a new jury will be impaneled on Monday. The Hennessy bribery cases will therefore not be tried this month, and the defense fight to prevent such an occurrence has been successful.
